    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_547007595" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/547007595" />
    <a title="Jane" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2634772-jane"><img alt="Jane" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1250561895p2/2634772.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/547007595?book_show_action=true">Feb 26, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jane" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jane" href="/user/show/2634772-jane">Jane</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2634772-jane?shelf=whitney-2012">whitney-2012</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer547007595" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1565134055493529066">Such an odd book. Here&apos;s what drove me nuts:<br/><br/>Vampires are all about sex. Seriously. You can say it is about agency, or whatever, but vampires, since the dawn of vampire lore, have been about sex. With that understanding in mind...<br/><br/>Carl is the unsexiest name for a vampire. Ever. Apologies to my friends named Carl. However the brutal truth is that your name is not as sexy as Lestat, Louis, Armand, Angelus, Spike, et al.<br/><br/>This is a trend I&apos;ve noticed in LDS fiction, but it was especially glaring here: </span>
  <span id="freeText1565134055493529066" style="display:none">Such an odd book. Here's what drove me nuts:<br /><br />Vampires are all about sex. Seriously. You can say it is about agency, or whatever, but vampires, since the dawn of vampire lore, have been about sex. With that understanding in mind...<br /><br />Carl is the unsexiest name for a vampire. Ever. Apologies to my friends named Carl. However the brutal truth is that your name is not as sexy as Lestat, Louis, Armand, Angelus, Spike, et al.<br /><br />This is a trend I've noticed in LDS fiction, but it was especially glaring here: sex is depicted in 2 ways. 1. Something awful (Moria mentions that she was raped 45 times, Sarah was sexually abused, vampires are sexually abused by their 'masters', Ben (the underage vampire) was repeatedly sexually abused). Or 2. something invisible/forbidden (for example: when a new good vampire couple hooks up they are reminded by Carl not to have sex (wow, awkward!).). No examples of good, healthy sexual relationships are depicted. Not even a come hither look and a fade to black. But... Perhaps it is better this way. The only sex scene I've read by an LDS author was the pillow fight scene in Breaking Dawn. Yeah, not that great.<br /><br />Vampires are also loaded with style. This is part of what makes them so stinking cool. Moria has good taste in swords, and she is described as looking like a punk rock goddess towards the end in a big fight she is having, but other than that these are some pretty bourgeois vampires. Even the chubby pirate vampire.<br /><br />A lot of the exposition felt repetitive. How many times are we going to have to hear about vampires not needing their wings to fly? And about the Anti-Nephi-Lehites? <br /><br />And then there were some truly painful and awkward moments where the heroine imagines being a sister-wife with Carl's deceased first wife! But no mention of her getting sealed to her murdered fiancé with whom apparently she was madly in love (it's fantasy- why not?). And since we're going there, I got mighty tired of Carl presiding over everything. I think even the author recognized what a bore Carl was and tried to tone down his authoritativeness by having him say 'please'. Despite Moria being a physically strong character, this book wasn't very favorable to women. The vampire society is set up as an upside-down (Satanic) version of the LDS Priesthood, complete with ordinations, covenants and rituals, with a woman on top. No alternative is presented in the book to show how women are empowered in Mormon culture.<br /><br />I have to give the author credit for writing such a gutsy book, and it certainly got a reaction from me. And he has a flair for writing action and very visual dramatic scenes. Lots of new ways of looking at vampires, some worked, some didn't. I am curious to check out the first book, mostly because I want to know more about the origin story of the vampires in this mythology. </span>
  <a data-text-id="1565134055493529066" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


